 33 |     # --- Explicitly configure parser logger level ---
 34 |     # This ensures debug messages from the parser are processed,

 36 |     parser_logger = logging.getLogger("glasir_api.core.parsers")

 38 |     if not any(isinstance(h, logging.StreamHandler) for h in parser_logger.handlers):

 51 |          else:

 57 |     # --- End logger configuration ---

<file_content path="glasir_timetable/INSTALLATION.md">
  1 | # Installation Instructions
  2 | 
  3 | ---
  4 | 
  5 | ## Prerequisites
  6 | 
  7 | - Python 3.7 or higher
  8 | - Playwright (for login and HTML parsing)
  9 | - A valid Glasir account
 10 | 
 11 | ---
 12 | 
 13 | ## Step 1: Install Dependencies
 14 | 
 15 | ```bash
 16 | pip3 install -r requirements.txt
 17 | python3 -m playwright install chromium
 18 | ```
 19 | 
 20 | ---
 21 | 
 22 | ## Step 2: Clone and Setup
 23 | 
 24 | ```bash
 25 | git clone https://github.com/yourusername/glasir_timetable.git
 26 | cd glasir_timetable
 27 | 
 28 | # Optional: create credentials file
 29 | echo '{"username": "your_username", "password": "your_password"}' > glasir_timetable/credentials.json
 30 | ```
 31 | 
 32 | If no credentials file is created, you will be prompted on first run.
 33 | 
 34 | ---
 35 | 
 36 | ## Step 3: Run the Application
 37 | 
 38 | ```bash
 39 | # Extract current week only
 40 | python3 -m glasir_timetable.main
 41 | 
 42 | # Extract current week plus 2 weeks forward and 2 weeks backward
 43 | python3 -m glasir_timetable.main --weekforward 2 --weekbackward 2
 44 | 
 45 | # Extract all available weeks
 46 | python3 -m glasir_timetable.main --all-weeks
 47 | ```
 48 | 
 49 | ---
 50 | 
 51 | ## Authentication Details
 52 | 
 53 | - First login uses Playwright to authenticate and save cookies.
 54 | - Subsequent requests use saved cookies (`cookies.json` by default).
 55 | - Cookies refresh automatically when expired.
 56 | 
 57 | ---
 58 | 
 59 | ### Per-Account Data Storage
 60 | 
 61 | All credentials, cookies, student info, and exported timetable data are stored **per user account** inside `glasir_timetable/accounts/USERNAME/`. This allows you to manage multiple Glasir accounts independently, with separate login sessions and data exports for each user.
 62 | 
 63 | 
 64 | ---
 65 | 
 66 | ## Advanced Configuration
 67 | 
 68 | ### Cookie Authentication
 69 | 
 70 | Enabled by default. Disable refresh with:
 71 | 
 72 | ```bash
 73 | python3 -m glasir_timetable.main --no-cookie-refresh
 74 | ```
 75 | 
 76 | ### Custom Output Directory
 77 | 
 78 | ```bash
 79 | python3 -m glasir_timetable.main --output-dir ~/my_timetable_data
 80 | ```
 81 | 
 82 | ### Update Teacher Map
 83 | 
 84 | ```bash
 85 | python3 -m glasir_timetable.main --teacherupdate --skip-timetable
 86 | ```
 87 | 
 88 | ### Debugging and Logging
 89 | 
 90 | ```bash
 91 | # Enable detailed logging
 92 | python3 -m glasir_timetable.main --log-level DEBUG --collect-error-details --collect-tracebacks
 93 | 
 94 | # Save logs to file
 95 | python3 -m glasir_timetable.main --log-file timetable_extraction.log
 96 | 
 97 | # Enable screenshots on errors
 98 | python3 -m glasir_timetable.main --enable-screenshots
 99 | ```
100 | 
101 | ---
102 | 
103 | ## Docker Usage (Optional)
104 | 
105 | ```bash
106 | docker build -t glasir_timetable .
107 | docker run -v $(pwd)/data:/app/data glasir_timetable --output-dir /app/data
108 | ```
109 | 
110 | ---
111 | 
112 | ## Troubleshooting
113 | 
114 | ### Authentication Issues
115 | 
116 | - Check credentials
117 | - Delete `cookies.json` to force fresh login
118 | - Verify internet connection
119 | 
120 | ### Extraction Issues
121 | 
122 | - Retry later if Glasir is down
123 | - Check logs for errors
124 | - Verify account access
125 | 
126 | ### Playwright Browser Issues
127 | 
128 | ```bash
129 | python3 -m playwright install --force
130 | ```
131 | 
132 | ---
133 | 
134 | ## Developer Setup (Brief)
135 | 
136 | - Use a **virtual environment**:
137 | 
138 | ```bash
139 | python3 -m venv venv
140 | source venv/bin/activate
141 | pip install -r requirements.txt
142 | python3 -m playwright install chromium
143 | ```
144 | 
145 | - **Run tests** (if available):
146 | 
147 | ```bash
148 | pytest
149 | ```
150 | 
151 | - Follow code style and submit pull requests for contributions.
152 | 
153 | ---
154 | 
155 | ## Next Steps
156 | 
157 | See [README.md](README.md) for features, architecture, and usage details.

<file_content path="glasir_timetable/README.md">
  1 | # Glasir Timetable Exporter
  2 | 
  3 | A powerful tool for extracting, processing, and exporting timetable data from Glasir's internal timetable system.
  4 | 
  5 | ---
  6 | 
  7 | ## Overview
  8 | 
  9 | This application authenticates with Glasir's system, fetches timetable and homework data via internal APIs, and exports the data as structured JSON files. It supports parallel extraction, teacher mapping, and flexible week range selection.
 10 | 
 11 | The tool uses a hybrid approach. It **automatically operates in an API-only mode** using `httpx` when valid authentication data (cookies and student info) is found for the selected profile, significantly speeding up extraction. If valid data is missing or expired, it seamlessly falls back to using Playwright browser automation for login and initial data retrieval. It caches teacher mappings and student info to optimize subsequent runs. All data, cookies, and credentials are stored per account under dedicated directories, enabling seamless management of multiple user accounts.
 12 | 
 13 | ---
 14 | 
 15 | ## Features
 16 | 
 17 | - **Automatic Hybrid Extraction:** Uses fast `httpx` API calls when possible (valid cookies/student info found), seamlessly falling back to Playwright browser automation for login/data retrieval only when necessary.
 18 | - **Efficient Authentication:** Reuses saved cookies and student info to bypass repeated Playwright logins.
 19 | - **Parallel fetching** of timetable and homework for multiple weeks.
 20 | - **Teacher initials resolution** with caching.
 21 | - **Homework integration** merged into timetable events.
 22 | - **Export to JSON** for easy integration with other tools.
 23 | - **Configurable week ranges** (current, past, future, or all).
 24 | - **Robust error handling** and detailed logging.
 25 | - **CLI interface** with comprehensive options.
 26 | - **Per-account data and cookie management** for multiple users.
 27 | - **Caching of teacher maps and student info** to optimize repeated runs.
 28 | 
 29 | ---
 30 | 
 31 | ## Architecture
 32 | 
 33 | The system features a modular architecture separating concerns like authentication, API interaction, data parsing, and storage.
 34 | 
 35 | For a detailed explanation and diagrams, see the [Architecture Documentation](docs/architecture.md).
 36 | 
 37 | ---
 38 | 
 39 | ## Usage
 40 | 
 41 | Basic example to extract the current week, plus 2 weeks forward and 2 weeks backward:
 42 | 
 43 | ```bash
 44 | python3 -m glasir_timetable --weekforward 2 --weekbackward 2
 45 | ```
 46 | 
 47 | ### Command-line Options
 48 | 
 49 | - `--username`: Glasir username (without @glasir.fo)
 50 | - `--password`: Glasir password
 51 | - `--credentials-file`: JSON file with credentials (default: `glasir_timetable/accounts/<username>/credentials.json`)
 52 | - `--weekforward`: Weeks forward to extract
 53 | - `--weekbackward`: Weeks backward to extract
 54 | - `--all-weeks`: Extract all available weeks
 55 | - `--output-dir`: Directory for exports (default: `output/`)
 56 | - `--headless`: Run browser headless (default: true)
 57 | - `--log-level`: Logging level (e.g., INFO, DEBUG)
 58 | - `--log-file`: Log to a specified file
 59 | - `--collect-error-details`: Collect detailed error info
 60 | - `--collect-tracebacks`: Collect tracebacks
 61 | - `--enable-screenshots`: Save screenshots on browser errors
 62 | - `--error-limit`: Max errors per category before stopping
 63 | - `--use-cookies`: Use saved cookies for login (default: true)
 64 | - `--cookie-path`: Path for cookies file (default: `glasir_timetable/accounts/<username>/cookies.json`)
 65 | - `--no-cookie-refresh`: Disable automatic cookie refresh
 66 | - `--teacherupdate`: Force update of the teacher cache
 67 | - `--skip-timetable`: Skip timetable extraction (e.g., only fetch homework)
 68 | 
 69 | ---
 70 | 
 71 | ## Output Format
 72 | 
 73 | Exports JSON files per week to the specified output directory. Example (`output/week_2023_10.json`):
 74 | 
 75 | ```json
 76 | {
 77 |   "weekInfo": {
 78 |     "weekNumber": 10,
 79 |     "year": 2023,
 80 |     "startDate": "2023-03-06",
 81 |     "endDate": "2023-03-12"
 82 |   },
 83 |   "events": [
 84 |     {
 85 |       "lessonId": "1234567",
 86 |       "startTime": "08:15",
 87 |       "endTime": "10:00",
 88 |       "dayOfWeek": 1, // Monday
 89 |       "subject": "Mathematics",
 90 |       "room": "A1.02",
 91 |       "teacher": "John Doe",
 92 |       "teacherInitials": "JDO",
 93 |       "description": "Homework: Complete exercises 1-10 on page 42"
 94 |     }
 95 |     // ... more events
 96 |   ]
 97 | }
 98 | ```
 99 | 
100 | ---
101 | 
102 | ## Installation
103 | 
104 | See [INSTALLATION.md](INSTALLATION.md) for detailed setup instructions.
105 | 
106 | ---
107 | 
108 | ## Testing
109 | 
110 | The project uses `pytest` for running tests. Mocks are utilized to isolate components during unit testing.
111 | 
112 | For details on the testing strategy and how to run tests, see the [Testing Documentation](docs/testing.md).
113 |

 28 |

 30 | # Removed imports from core.*, data.*, and unused shared.*
 31 | 
 32 | # Imports for the current main structure
 33 | from glasir_timetable.interface.cli import parse_args, select_account

 35 | from glasir_timetable.interface.application import Application
 36 | from glasir_timetable.interface.orchestrator import run_extraction
 37 | from glasir_timetable.storage.profile_manager import ProfileManager # Use ProfileManager for account/profile handling

 41 | # Removed local duplicate function prompt_for_credentials (handled by interface.cli)
 42 | 
 43 | async def main():
 44 |     """
 45 |     Main entry point for the Glasir Timetable application.
 46 |     """
 47 |     # Initialize statistics
 48 |     clear_errors()  # Clear any errors from previous runs
 49 |     update_stats("start_time", time.time(), increment=False)
 50 | 
 51 |     args = parse_args() # Use imported function
 52 |     
 53 |     # If no log file provided, use default output/logs/glasir_timetable.log
 54 |     if not args.log_file:
 55 |         log_dir = os.path.join("output", "logs")
 56 |         os.makedirs(log_dir, exist_ok=True)
 57 |         args.log_file = os.path.join(log_dir, "glasir_timetable.log")
 58 |     # Ensure directory for log file exists (handles custom paths)
 59 |     log_dir = os.path.dirname(args.log_file)
 60 |     if log_dir and not os.path.exists(log_dir):
 61 |         os.makedirs(log_dir, exist_ok=True)
 62 | 
 63 |     # Generate date string for log filename
 64 |     date_str = datetime.now().strftime("%Y-%m-%d_%H-%M-%S")
 65 | 
 66 |     # Create dated log filename
 67 |     base_log_file = args.log_file
 68 |     if base_log_file.endswith('.log'):
 69 |         dated_log_file = base_log_file[:-4] + f"_{date_str}.log"
 70 |     else:
 71 |         dated_log_file = base_log_file + f"_{date_str}.log"
 72 | 
 73 |     # Create latest log filename in same directory
 74 |     latest_log_file = os.path.join(log_dir, "latest.log")
 75 | 
 76 | 
 77 |     # Configure logging based on command-line arguments
 78 |     log_level = getattr(logging, args.log_level)
 79 |     if args.log_file:
 80 |         formatter = logging.Formatter('[%(asctime)s] %(levelname)s - %(message)s', datefmt='%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S')
 81 | 
 82 |         # Handler for dated log file (append mode)
 83 |         dated_handler = logging.FileHandler(dated_log_file, mode='a')
 84 |         dated_handler.setFormatter(formatter)
 85 |         logger.addHandler(dated_handler)
 86 | 
 87 |         # Handler for latest.log (overwrite mode)
 88 |         latest_handler = logging.FileHandler(latest_log_file, mode='w')
 89 |         latest_handler.setFormatter(formatter)
 90 |         logger.addHandler(latest_handler)
 91 | 
 92 |     # Set the log level
 93 |     logger.setLevel(log_level)
 94 |     for handler in logger.handlers:
 95 |         handler.setLevel(log_level)
 96 | 
 97 |     # ---- ACCOUNT SELECTION ----
 98 |     profile_manager = ProfileManager.get_instance() # Get instance for checking
 99 | 
100 |     if args.account:
101 |         # Account specified via command line
102 |         selected_username = args.account
103 |         profile_created = False # Assume existing profile when specified via arg
104 |         logger.info(f"Account '{selected_username}' specified via --account argument.")
105 | 
106 |         # Validate if the specified profile exists
107 |         if not profile_manager.profile_exists(selected_username):
108 |             logger.error(f"Error: Account profile '{selected_username}' specified via --account does not exist.")
109 |             sys.exit(1) # Exit gracefully
110 |         else:
111 |             logger.debug(f"Validated existence of profile: {selected_username}")
112 | 
113 |     else:
114 |         # No account specified, use interactive selection
115 |         logger.debug("No --account argument provided, proceeding with interactive selection.")
116 |         # Use imported function
117 |         selected_username, profile_created = await select_account() # Capture the tuple
118 | 
119 |     if selected_username is None:
120 |         logger.error("No accounts found. Please create an account before running the timetable extraction.")
121 |         return
122 | 
123 |     # Use imported function
124 |     # Pass the profile_created flag to load_config
125 |     config = await load_config(args, selected_username, profile_created=profile_created)
126 | 
127 |     # Removed outdated Playwright setup and service factory logic.
128 |     # This is now handled within the Application/Orchestrator structure.
129 |     from glasir_timetable.interface.application import Application
130 |     # Instantiate Application with the loaded config
131 |     app = Application(config)
132 | 
133 |     # Run the main extraction process via the orchestrator
134 |     await run_extraction(app)
135 | 
136 | # Execution completed
137 | update_stats("end_time", time.time(), increment=False)
138 | start_time = stats.get("start_time")
139 | end_time = stats.get("end_time")
140 | if start_time is None or end_time is None:
141 |     elapsed_time = 0.0
142 | else:
143 |     elapsed_time = end_time - start_time
144 | logger.info(f"Execution completed in {elapsed_time:.2f} seconds")
145 |

147 |     import argparse
148 |     import sys
149 |     import asyncio
150 |     import cProfile
151 |     import pstats
152 |     import io
153 |     from pathlib import Path
154 | 
155 |     # Ensure project root is in sys.path (redundant if first block ran, but safe)
156 |     project_root = os.path.abspath(os.path.dirname(__file__))
157 |     if project_root not in sys.path:
158 |         sys.path.insert(0, project_root)
159 | 
160 |     # Install uvloop for potential performance gains
161 |     try:
162 |         import uvloop
163 |         uvloop.install()
164 |         logger.info("Using uvloop for asyncio event loop.")
165 |     except ImportError:
166 |         logger.warning("uvloop not found, using standard asyncio event loop.")
167 |         pass # Fallback to standard asyncio loop if uvloop is not installed
168 | 
169 |     # Check for --profile argument *without* consuming other arguments
170 |     profile_enabled = "--profile" in sys.argv
171 |     if profile_enabled:
172 |         # Remove --profile so it doesn't interfere with the main parser
173 |         sys.argv.remove("--profile")
174 |         # The main() function will now receive the original args minus --profile
175 |     
176 |     # No need to reassign sys.argv here, main() will use the modified sys.argv
177 | 
178 |     if profile_enabled:
179 |         profile_output = "profile_output.prof"
180 |         pr = cProfile.Profile()
181 |         pr.enable()
182 | 
183 |         try:
184 |             asyncio.run(main())
185 |         finally:
186 |             pr.disable()
187 |             s = io.StringIO()
188 |             ps = pstats.Stats(pr, stream=s).sort_stats('cumulative')
189 |             ps.print_stats(30)
190 |             print("Profiling results (top 30 by cumulative time):")
191 |             print(s.getvalue())
192 |             ps.dump_stats(profile_output)
193 |             print(f"Full profile data saved to {profile_output}")
194 |     else:
195 |         asyncio.run(main())
